instance dt_constellation : DTDFVocab:Constellation [
    base:desc "The incubator Digital Twin is orchestrated around a tight integration of hardware, software, and simulation models. Data is collected from two inside‑temperature sensors and one outside temperature sensor by a Raspberry‑Pi controller and a low‑level driver. These readings are broadcast over a message broker (RabbitMQ in the repository) to the Twin runtime. A time‑series database persists the raw sensor streams and feeds them into a real‑time dashboard generated by a lightweight web UI. The Twin runtime hosts two prediction models (Model A with two free parameters and Model B with four). Model B is used for anomaly detection and state estimation. A Kalman‑filter algorithm processes the incoming streams and the model‑predicted temperatures to flag deviations. When an anomaly is detected, a self‑adaptation routine schedules a new experiment: it modifies the controller set‑point, triggers a data‑collection run, then retrains Model B using an automatic calibration routine. The calibrated parameters are fed back into the Kalman filter and optionally into the controller for automated re‑configuration. For what‑if scenarios, the Twin executes co‑simulations that replay past or live sensor data through the models to assess alternative controller settings. All these components—data acquisition, message bus, simulation models, calibration, monitoring, adaptation, and visualization—are coordinated by a Python‑based orchestration layer that ensures deterministic ordering of events. The architecture follows a modular, service‑oriented pattern where each functional block (data ingestion, simulation, monitoring, adaptation, UI) is a self‑contained service communicating over MQTT/RabbitMQ, while the Twin maintains a coherent causal state that links the physical process with its digital counterpart."
]

instance life_cycle_stages : DTDFVocab:EvolutionStage [
    base:desc "Development of the incubator digital twin begins by building two thermal simulation models (a two-parameter and a four-parameter model) that represent the heatbed, fan and insulated container. Sensor data from two inside and one outside temperature probe are collected in real-time and fed to a calibration algorithm that estimates the model parameters. Once calibrated the model is deployed into the DT framework, where it runs alongside the Raspberry Pi controller of the physical twin and continuously simulates future temperature profiles. Operation of the DT is governed by monitors that compare simulated and measured temperatures against safety and optimality constraints; when violations are detected the monitor triggers either automatic corrective actions via a supervisory controller or hands control to a human operator. Transition between stages is managed through periodic recalibration, and lifecycle governance is achieved by embedding calibration and monitoring as core DT services."
]

instance fidelity_and_validity_considerations : DTDFVocab:FidelityConsideration [
